If you want to add a custom user role or simply don’t want to use a plugin, then you can try this method instead. You will be able to modify it to meet your needs.

You’ll need to add the following code to your WordPress functions.php file or a site-specific plugin.

```
// Limit media library access
  
add_filter( &#39;ajax_query_attachments_args&#39;, &#39;wpb_show_current_user_attachments&#39; );
 
function wpb_show_current_user_attachments( $query ) {
    $user_id = get_current_user_id();
    if ( $user_id &amp;&amp; !current_user_can(&#39;activate_plugins&#39;) &amp;&amp; !current_user_can(&#39;edit_others_posts
&#39;) ) {
        $query[&#39;author&#39;] = $user_id;
    }
    return $query;
} 
```
This code uses current_user_can function to check if the user has the capability to activate plugins or edit other user’s posts. If they don’t, then it changes the query used to display media files and limit it to user’s ID.

Also for Image hotlinking protection you can use this in your .htaccess
```
#disable hotlinking of images with forbidden or custom image option
RewriteEngine on
RewriteCond %{HTTP_REFERER} !^$
RewriteCond %{HTTP_REFERER} !^http(s)?://(www\.)?yourdomain.com [NC]
RewriteCond %{HTTP_REFERER} !^http(s)?://(www\.)?google.com [NC]
RewriteRule \.(jpg|jpeg|png|gif)$ – [NC,F,L] 
```

This code only allows images to be displayed if the request is originating from yourdomain.com or Google.com. Don’t forget to replace yourdomain.com with your own domain name.

